<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-673-731  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 673 731.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Dec 3 1990 v24 n49 p63(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Using graphical interfaces to take a closer look.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Hurwicz, Michael.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A graphical user interface (GUI) that uses icons and linesrepresenting network links is often superior to character-basedtools for managing networks.andP;  GUIs are especially helpful inmanaging large networks.andP;  Network management staff can interpret apicture, especially one in color, much more quickly than they caninterpret the hundreds of one-line alerts typical ofcharacter-based systems.andP;  Failure-patterns are also easier tointerpret with GUIs.andP;  One problem of GUIs is their tendency tolure network management staff into complacency.andP;  GUIs also demandmore maintenance than character-based systems.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Graphical User InterfaceNetwork ManagementComparison.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotographtable.andO;Caption:   Network managers rate net functions. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>